standing stock options\n- All xAI-originated options/RSUs/RSAs presented on an as-converted basis (0.1433 SpaceX shares per xAI award, on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis — i.e., effectively ~0.7165 post-split)\n\n### H. Cover Page and Capitalization\n- **Shares of Class A common stock offered** in the IPO\n- **Class A and Class B shares outstanding immediately before and after the offering**\n- **Pro forma capitalization table** share counts\n- **Underwriters\' over-allotment option** share count\n\n### I. Beneficial Ownership Table\n- Pre-offering ownership based on **6,932,508,000 Class A** and **5,602,790,410 Class B** shares outstanding as of May 1, 2026, after giving effect to the Class C Reclassification, the Preferred Conversion, and the 2026 Stock Split\n- Post-offering ownership percentages and share counts\n\n### J. Dilution Section\n- **Pro forma net tangible book value per share**\n- **Dilution per share to new investors**\n- Sensitivity disclosures (each $1.00 change in IPO price; each change in shares offered)\n\n### K. Use of Proceeds\n- Sensitivity of net proceeds to per-share IPO price changes\n\n### L. Auditor\'s Report\n- The auditor\'s report date is bifurcated: March 30, 2026 for the base opinion, with an explanatory paragraph dated **May 7, 2026** specifically addressing the effects of the common-control reorganization and the stock split discussed in Note 1\n\n---\n\n## 3. Why an Analyst Must Apply the Adjustment Factor Before Drawing Valuation Conclusions\n\nAn analyst comparing pre-split secondary market transaction prices (such as the Forge Global $634 peak on April 1, 2026) to post-filing per-share metrics in the S-1 must divide the pre-split price by 5 (yielding $126.80) before any meaningful comparison. The reasons are:\n\n### (a) Unit-of-measure mismatch\nThe $634 Forge Global price is denominated in **pre-split shares**. Every per-share figure in the S-1 — net loss per share, pro forma net loss per share, weighted-average share counts, net tangible book value per share, and the IPO price range — is denominated in **post-split shares**. Comparing $634 to a post-split per-share metric without adjustment conflates two different units of measurement; the resulting ratio would be overstated by a factor of 5.\n\n### (b) Market capitalization and valuation multiple errors\nIf an analyst multiplied the unadjusted $634 by the post-split share count (e.g., the ~12.5 billion Class A + Class B shares outstanding as of May 1, 2026), the implied equity value would be **5x overstated** — roughly $7.9 trillion instead of the economically correct ~$1.6 trillion. Any P/E, EV/EBITDA, or price-to-sales multiple derived from such a calculation would be similarly distorted, leading to materially wrong conclusions about relative valuation versus peers.\n\n### (c) Dilution and ownership analysis errors\nThe beneficial ownership table, the pro forma capitalization table, and the dilution section all present share counts on a post-split basis. An analyst who fails to adjust pre-split transaction prices would miscalculate:\n- Pre-IPO vs. post-IPO ownership percentages\n- Dilution to new investors\n- The economic impact of the Preferred Conversion and Class C Reclassification\n\n### (d) Preferred stock and equity-award conversion errors\nThe SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock conversion rate was reset from an implied 10 shares to 50 shares per preferred share. The xAI preferred conversion ratios (0.1433 shares per preferred share) are explicitly disclosed "on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis." An analyst who ignores the split factor would misstate the dilutive impact of these conversions on the fully diluted share count and on pro forma EPS.\n\n### (e) Consistency with the filing\'s own presentation\nThe S-1 itself imposes the adjustment: it states that "all share and per share information included in this prospectus have been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split for all periods presented." An analyst who does not apply the same 1/5 factor to external pre-split price observations is comparing apples to oranges — the filing\'s historical per-share data has been re-based, but external secondary-market prices quoted before May 4, 2026 have not. The adjustment factor is the bridge that restores comparability.\n\n### (f) Avoiding spurious "discount" or "premium" conclusions\nWithout adjustment, an analyst might conclude that the IPO price (post-split) represents a deep discount to the $634 secondary-market peak — when in fact the economically equivalent post-split comparison price is $126.80. Conversely, comparing post-split per-share book value or EPS to an unadjusted $634 would produce a falsely elevated multiple. Either error could lead to incorrect buy/sell/hold recommendations or mispriced IPO demand.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Item | Pre-Split Value | Adjustment | Post-Split Equivalent |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Forge Global peak price (Apr 1, 2026) | $634.00 / share | ÷ 5 | **$126.80 / share** |\n| SpaceX preferred conversion rate | 10 shares/preferred share | × 5 | 50 shares/preferred share |\n| xAI preferred → SpaceX conversion ratio | 0.1433 shares (pre-split basis) | × 5 | ~0.7165 shares |\n| xAI Series A cash election price | $75.46 / share (pre-split basis) | ÷ 5 | ~$15.09 / share |\n| Par value (Class A/B/C) | $0.001 | unchanged | $0.001 |\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement filed May 20, 2026 (Note 1 — Nature of Business; Note 13 — Shareholders\' Equity; Consolidated Statements of Operations; Pro Forma EPS reconciliation; Beneficial Ownership Table; Cover Page; Capitalization; Dilution sections)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://forgeglobal.com/spacex_stock",\n      "name": "Forge Global — SpaceX private market pricing and secondary market activity (context for pre-split secondary market transaction prices)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://forgeglobal.com/insights/how-to-invest-in-spacex-pre-ipo",\n      "name": "Forge Global Insights — How To Invest in SpaceX Pre-IPO (secondary market valuation context)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
